        <main class="main-content">
            <header class="project-header">
                <h1>Prolitec Aera</h1>
                
                <div class="project-meta">
                    <span><strong>Role:</strong> Lead Product Designer</span>
                    <span><strong>Client:</strong> Prolitec</span>
                    <span><strong>Platform:</strong> Alexa & Google Home Skills</span>
                </div>
                
                <div class="project-summary">
                    Home scenting UX for mood + environment. Designing voice and app interfaces for Prolitec's first consumer-facing IoT product, creating an elegant and reliable experience that conveys technical confidence while maintaining the ephemeral, luxurious nature of home scenting.
                </div>
            </header>
            
            <section class="content-section" id="problem">
                <h2>User Problem</h2>
                <p>Users needed a convenient way to control their electric scent diffuser without getting up or opening their phone.</p>
                
                <p>Prolitec was launching its first consumer-facing IoT product and needed a voice and app interface that conveyed reliability, elegance, and technical confidence.</p>
                
                <div class="image-placeholder">
                    <img src="/img/Prolitec/pinkdiffuser.png" alt="Shark/Ninja Robot Vacuum Hero Image" style="width: 100%; height: auto; border-radius: 8px;">
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section class="content-section" id="strategy">
                <h2>Strategy</h2>
                
                <h3>My Role</h3>
                <p>I was the lead product designer on the Alexa and Google Home skills, and worked with a fellow designer who was tackling the mobile use case.</p>
                
                <p>I brought the more ephemeral elements of home scenting as well as the high-end, tech forward legacy of Prolitec through in the VUI.</p>
                
                <h3>Approach</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Research:</strong> A lot of copy research went into how people think about scents and what they would actually say to Alexa about their home scents</li>
                    <li><strong>Refine requirements:</strong> The device was first of its kind on the market, and we were providing the end-to-end IoT solution. I worked with engineering to understand what features were possible</li>
                    <li><strong>Design:</strong> I designed the VUI including the VUI diagram, copy and tone writing, introduction text, and worked with mobile teams to sync with the mobile app</li>
                    <li><strong>Ship:</strong> I and another designer worked to synchronize the iOS and Android apps with the voice skill and the copy and shipped them at the same time</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
            
            <section class="content-section" id="process">
                <h2>Process</h2>
                <p>For this product, working to develop the brand through the UI and voice-skill was critical, as this was one of their first consumer-facing products.</p>
                
                <p>Home scenting is personal, ephemeral, and luxurious.</p>
                
                <p>But typical IoT feature possibilities — scheduling, control-tasks, and setup — can take away from a whimsical experience.</p>
            </section>
            
            <section class="content-section" id="solution">
                <h2>Solution</h2>
                <p>The company was tech-forward vs. scent-forward.</p>
                
                <p>We repositioned the brand tone from purely technical to sensory-forward, using scent moods and sound design to elevate the emotional layer of the experience.</p>
                
                <p>While users often enjoy personalizing robots with names, we found that naming a scent diffuser felt unnatural. We addressed this with a default alias system that prioritized ease and immersion.</p>
                
                <p>The user interface of the mobile UI matched the design of the device with a large dial at the center. Scent-inspired colors and patterns personalized the UI and were driven home in the VUI through tone and sound effects.</p>
                
                <div class="image-placeholder">
                    <img src="/img/Prolitec/appUI.png" alt="Shark/Ninja Robot Vacuum Hero Image" style="width: 100%; height: auto; border-radius: 8px;">
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section class="content-section" id="design">
                <h2>Design Details</h2>
                <p>"Alexa, ask Aera to adjust intensity" was awkward, but it's where we started with engineering for the scent intensity feature.</p>
                
                <p>Complexity comes in when you have multiple diffusers.</p>
                
                <p>"Alexa, ask Aera 1 to turn it down" is much more natural but took some finessing and collaboration with copy and engineering to get right.</p>
                
                <p>Determining what "down" meant — 1, 2 scent notches — was also a collaboration with business and had to be determined across the app & voice skill.</p>
                
                <h3>VUI Design Considerations</h3>
                <p>A huge UX barrier on VUIs was the constant need to define devices using names. Users would receive an inquiry as to the name of their device in most cases based on hardware limitations.</p>
                
                <p>We navigated this by keeping Alexa's queries short and to the point, and offering strategic paths and queries to different functionalities in the VUI. I designed default names into the skill for Aera, which we did not do on Shark, because it's less natural to name a diffuser than a roaming robot.</p>
                
                <div class="image-placeholder">
                    <img src="/img/Prolitec/prolitecVUI.png" alt="Shark/Ninja Robot Vacuum Hero Image" style="width: 100%; height: auto; border-radius: 8px;">
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section class="content-section" id="insights">
                <h2>Insights</h2>
                
                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h3>Setting a Mood</h3>
                    <p>Enabling the brand to communicate competence and credibility came first before any ephemeral features as IoT users are often frustrated. I drove this throughout the design process.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h3>Engineering Partnership is Key</h3>
                    <p>Working with engineering to co-create feasible fallback interaction paths for unsupported utterances like naming your scent diffuser is crucial to avoid awkwardness in voice interfaces and prevent user discomfort in their homes.</p>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <nav class="navigation">
